CHILE DAYBOOK: Authorities May Vote on HidroAysen Power Project

-- B y   R a n d y   W o o d s   a n d   E d u a r d o   T h o m s o n
-- 
2011-05-09T03:00:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-09/chile-daybook-authorities-may-vote-on-hidroaysen-power-project.html
Officials in the southern city of
Coyhaique may vote on whether to grant an environmental license
to the HidroAysen power project in Patagonia.  WHAT TO WATCH:
* Chile ’s central bank discloses trade data for April on its
website at 8:30 a.m. New York time.  ECONOMY:
*Consumer prices rose 0.3 percent in April from March, the
National Statistics Institute said in a report. The median
estimate of 16 economists surveyed by Bloomberg was for a 0.4
percent increase. Annual inflation reached 3.2 percent, down
from 3.4 percent a month earlier. Economists expected an annual
rate of 3.3 percent, according to the median of 13 forecasts.  EQUITIES:
*The Ipsa index rose 0.5 percent to 4,813.64.
*CFR Pharmaceuticals SA gained 20 percent to 115.63 pesos. The
Chilean drugs developer has increased 37 percent since its
initial public offering of shares.
*Cia. Cervecerias Unidas SA increased 2.2 percent to 5,590
pesos, the largest gain in six weeks. Chile’s largest brewer was
upgraded to “buy” from “neutral” at Bank of America Corp.
*Colbun SA rose 0.4 percent to 141.8 pesos. Santiago-based
brokerage Celfin Capital reiterated a “buy” rating for Chile’s
third-largest power producer by installed generation capacity.
*Empresas CMPC SA rose 0.8 percent to 25,199 pesos. The
country’s second-largest pulp exporter posted first-quarter
profit of $141 million, up from $79.5 million a year earlier.  MARKETS:
*Chile’s peso gained 0.2 percent to 467.96 per  U.S. dollar .
*The central bank confirmed it will keep buying dollars at $50
million a day as it published its monthly  financing calendar  to
run from May 9 through June 8.
*Interest-rate swap rates and breakeven inflation fell. The one-
year swap rate fell five basis points, or 0.05 percentage point,
to 5.56 percent, completing a nine basis point decline on the
week. The six-month swap rate fell seven basis points to 5.31
percent.
*One-year breakeven inflation fell 10 basis points to 3.84
percent. Two-year breakeven inflation fell three basis points to
3.66 percent.
*Foreign investors in the Chilean peso forwards market increased
bets that the peso would fall against the dollar by $119 million
to $2 billion on May 4, according to central bank data.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
